<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-014-189 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 559 984</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Nov 11 1991 n346 p76(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Morris got what he deserved: let hackers heed the lesson:intruding without authorization is against the law. (U.S. SupremeCourt rules on Robert T. Morris, Jr. hacker case) (Final Word)(Column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dorn, Philip H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Supreme Court's rejection of an appeal by Robert Morris tooverturn Morris' conviction under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Actof 1986 sends a strong message to computer hackers.andP;  Morris arguedthat he had not intended to do harm when he injected a worm intoInternet, only to test the network's security.andP;  However, theruling by the court deems that any attempt to enter a computersystem without authorization is illegal.andP;  In reality, it is verydifficult to defend Morris' position that he did not mean to doany harm because just looking around caused some installations onInternet to shut down.andP;  The act is not perfect and it needsclarifying, but it does send the right message to deter peoplefrom entering computer systems without permission.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986.andO;Topic:     Legal IssuesComputer hackersData security.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (Cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>